\paragraph{Part II} \mbox{} \\
The Lagrangian of the optimization problem can be stated as follows (where $a_i \geq 0$ and $r_i \geq 0$ are Lagrangian multipliers):

$$ L(\textbf{w}, b, \xi_i, a_i, r_i) = \frac{1}{2} \textbf{w}^T \textbf{S}_t \textbf{w} + C \sum^n_{i=1}\xi_i - \sum^n_{i=1}a_i(y_i(\textbf{w}^T x_i + b) - 1 + \xi_i) - \sum^n_{i=1}r_i\xi_i $$

The dual problem to optimize is then:

$$ \max_{a_i > 0} \min{\textbf{w}, b, \xi_i, r_i} L(\textbf{w}, b, \xi_i, a_i, r_i) $$

The optimal $\textbf{w}$, $b$ and $\xi_i$ will satisfy the condition that the partial derivatives with regards to these parameters will be 0.

$$ \frac{\partial L}{\partial \textbf{w}} = \frac{1}{2} (\textbf{S}_t + \textbf{S}_t^T) \textbf{w} - \sum_{i=1}^{n} a_i y_i x_i = \textbf{S}_t \textbf{w} - \sum_{i=1}^{n} a_i y_i x_i = 0 \Leftrightarrow $$
$$ \textbf{S}_t \textbf{w} = \sum_{i=1}^{n} a_i y_i x_i \Leftrightarrow $$
$$ \textbf{w} = \textbf{S}_t^{-1} \sum_{i=1}^{n} a_i y_i x_i $$

\bigskip

$$ \frac{\partial L}{\partial b} = \sum_{i=1}{n}a_i y_i = 0 \Leftrightarrow $$
$$ a^T \textbf{y} = 0 $$

\bigskip

$$ \frac{\partial L}{\partial \xi_i} = C - a_i - r_i = 0 \Leftrightarrow $$
$$ r_i + a_i = C $$

